Part 1

The morning shift at the hospital began at six. The corridors were filled with the grey, cold light of an early dawn that hadn't yet cleared the smoke from the nearby railway yard. 

Adarsh walked toward the casualty ward, his boots heavy on the stone floor. He hadn't slept for more than two hours during the night, his eyes carrying the dry, burning sensation of a long, anxious watch.

The crowd near the ICU door had not dispersed. They were still there, sitting on the cold floor with their backs against the green-painted brick wall, their hands empty. 

The auto driver, the flower seller, and the school teacher were all silent. Nobody was holding flowers today, and nobody was whispering.

Ananya sat on the same wooden chair near the corner. The bamboo walking stick with the tiny strip of red cloth was leaning against her shoulder. 

She wasn't looking at the ICU doors anymore. She was looking down at the rubber slippers kept carefully under the empty stretcher frame near the wall—both slippers, clean and placed side by side.

Adarsh slowed his pace as he reached the swing doors. 

The ICU door was open. Inside, the monitor beside table nine was silent, the green screen completely blank, and the black power cord was unplugged and wound neatly around the metal stand. 

The white sheet on the bed was pulled all the way to the top, showing only the outline of a thin shoulder and the long, still frame of the legs underneath.

The senior nurse was standing near the steel medicine cabinet, sorting the unused ampoules of adrenaline back into the plastic partition tray. She saw Adarsh enter, set the tray down on the shelf, and turned to face him.

"At four-fifteen, sir," she said, her voice dropping. "The blood pressure dropped suddenly. We gave the dopamine infusion, but the heart was too tired to respond."

Adarsh stood near the side of the bed. He didn't pull the sheet back to look at the face. 

As a doctor, he had pulled back a hundred sheets during his career. He had checked the pupils for light response, felt the cold neck for the carotid pulse, and signed the time of death on the margins of the case files. 

But he didn't touch this sheet. He simply looked at the white outline under the cloth.

The distance between the anatomy dissection table in 1995 and this silent ICU bed in 2018 was twenty-three years. He had spent the entire night in his quarters thinking of the questions he would ask when Vikram finally woke up. 

*Why didn't you write to me?* 

*Where did the company go?* 

*Who was Rehman?*

Now, the sheet was closed. The questions had stayed in his own head, and there was no other room in the world where the answers would ever be spoken.

"A lady is waiting for you in the visitor's room," the nurse said, closing the medicine drawer with a soft click. "Dr. Sen. The psychiatrist from the Kolkata medical college. She has the patient's records from 2016."

Adarsh looked at the white sheet one last time. Then he turned, walked out of the ICU, passed the crowd sitting silently against the wall, and went toward the visitor's wing. 

Near the corner of the corridor, the old tea seller was starting his coal stove. The blue flame groaned as it caught the kerosene, smelling of oil and the dry, cold air of the morning.

[End of Part 1]
